The MLBStandings2016 dataset records many variables for Major League Baseball (MLB) teams from the 2016 regular season. Dont worry if you are unfamiliar with baseball terminology as some of the acronyms for variable names have little meaning. TASK 1.3 Use a best subsets procedure to determine which four predictors together would explain the most variability in WinPct. Write down the predictors in this model and its R-squared value.



# Use regsubsets to perform best subsets regression
best_subsets <- regsubsets(WinPct ~ ., data = MLBStandings2016, nvmax = length(names(MLBStandings2016)) - 1)  # -1 because we exclude the response variable

# Extract the summary
best_subsets_summary <- summary(best_subsets)

# Get the best four-predictor model
best_four_predictors <- coef(best_subsets, id = 4)

# Extract the names of the predictors, excluding the intercept
predictor_names <- names(best_four_predictors)[-1]  # -1 to exclude the intercept

# Fit the best four-predictor model to get R-squared
best_four_model <- lm(formula = as.formula(paste("WinPct ~", paste(predictor_names, collapse = " + "))), data = MLBStandings2016)

model_summary_best_four <- summary(best_four_model)

# Display the predictors
print(predictor_names)

TASK 1.5 Assuming that the three procedures did not all give the same four-predictor model, which model would you prefer? Explain why.

The Best Subsets Model, incorporating the predictors Runs, Doubles, Saves, and WHIP, emerges as the preferable model for predicting WinPct in the context of the MLBStandings2016 dataset. This model adheres to the principle of parsimony, utilizing only four predictors while still achieving a substantial R2R2 value of 0.8885, indicating a robust explanatory power. Moreover, it boasts the lowest Mallows Cp (10.49), suggesting a harmonious balance between model complexity and predictive precision. While the backward elimination model showed a higher R2R2 value, its potential for overfitting, evidenced by a larger number of predictors and a higher Mallows Cp, raises concerns about its applicability to new, unseen data. Conversely, the forward selection model fails to provide any predictive utility, incorporating no predictors and achieving an R2R2 of 0. Thus, in the pursuit of a model that is both explanatory and generalizable, the Best Subsets Model stands out as the most viable among the three.

2. NCbirths

The file NCbirths contains data on a sample of 1450 birth records that statistician John Holcomb selected from the North Carolina State Center for Health and Environmental Statistics. One of the questions of interest is how the birth weights (in ounces) of the babies might be related to the mothers race. The variable MomRace codes the mothers race as white, black, hispanic, or other. When you use R to run a regression model using MomRace to predict BirthWeightOz, R sets up indicator variables for each of these categories.

TASK 2.2 Explain what each of the coefficients in your fitted model tells us about race and birth weights for babies born in North Carolina.

In the fitted model analyzing birth weights in North Carolina, the average birth weight for babies born to black mothers (the reference group) is approximately 110.563 ounces. Babies born to Hispanic and white mothers are on average 7.955 and 7.309 ounces heavier, respectively, than those born to black mothers. Theres also a suggested increase of 6.583 ounces for the other race category compared to black mothers, though this difference is marginally significant. While the model indicates associations between the mothers race and birth weight, it doesnt imply causation, and other factors might influence these observed differences.

TASK 2.3.1 The individual t-tests for the coefficients of the indicator variables.

The t-tests assess if the coefficients of the indicator variables significantly differ from zero. For MomRacehispanic, a t-value of 3.766 and p-value of 0.000173 indicate babies born to Hispanic mothers are significantly, on average, 7.955 ounces heavier than those of black mothers. For MomRaceother, the t-value is 1.926 with a p-value of 0.054298, suggesting a marginally significant difference. The MomRacewhite coefficient, with a t-value of 5.147 and p-value of 3.01e-07, shows babies born to white mothers are significantly, on average, 7.309 ounces heavier than those of black mothers.

TASK 2.3.2 The value of R-squared.

The R2R2 value is 0.01938, indicating that about 1.938% of the variability in birth weight is explained by the mothers race. This low R2R2 suggests that while theres an association between the mothers race and birth weight, many other unaccounted factors in the model likely influence birth weight.

TASK 2.3.3 The overall F-test in the ANOVA table.

The overall F-statistic of 9.528 with a p-value of 3.118e-06 tests if all regression coefficients (barring the intercept) are zero. The low p-value indicates that at least one coefficient differs from zero, suggesting a statistically significant association between the mothers race and babys birth weight when considering all races collectively.

Multicollinearity is a concern in regression analysis when two or more predictor variables are highly correlated, which can affect the reliability of coefficient estimates. The Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) is a common metric to assess multicollinearity. Generally, a VIF exceeding 10 indicates high multicollinearity. Analyzing the VIF values from the provided full_model, all predictors have VIF values well below 10. Specifically, the highest VIF is for LiverTest at 3.024861, which is still relatively low. Therefore, based on these VIF values, there are no serious concerns about multicollinearity in the model.
